 Good entry.
 
 >>
 If the impact of influenza is roughly divided into "infectivity" and "toxicity," the type of influenza this time is "normal level of infectivity and weak toxicity," and has not reached the "humanity is doomed" level.
 <<
 
 This is the important part, isn't it? I'm a little panicky and worried, though I'm nervous all at once because of the suspected cases in Japan.
 
 >>
 Certainly, there is a possibility of mutation. But if we consider it as an extension of ordinary influenza, our intuition is that it is impossible to have a scenario in which a mutation that reduces the host's chances of survival has an advantage.
 <<
 
 But the following mutations have an advantage, don't they?
 - the incubation period is prolonged
 - become more infectious
 - More time to remain active after adhering to non-living objects such as train straps
 - Increase in proliferation rate
 - Stronger against water, medicated soaps, etc.
 - Reduced apparent symptoms.
 
 Then, under the situation of "quarantine, test, and treat as soon as influenza-like symptoms appear," the following mutations are not neutral because both developing the disease and killing the host are the same for the virus in terms of "losing the opportunity to reproduce.
 - Tamiflu will not work.
 - Increases toxicity (increases the rate at which people who contract it die)
 
 I myself wonder, "Do mutations happen all the time?" I myself think "Mutations don't happen that often.
 
 *1241153959*emacsclient useful!
 If you do M-x server-start in carbonEmacs and then do $ emacsclient HOGE in the terminal, HOGE will be opened as one buffer of the already opened carbonEmacs. I didn't have to do any particular configuration.
 
 Add (server-start) to .emacs.el to run at carbonEmacs startup, and export EDITOR=emacsclient to .bash_profile to run at terminal startup.
 I wrote "I'm so happy. I'm happy for you.
 
 <hr>
 I forgot to write something important: if you write in emacsclient, use C-x # to exit.
 
